  "prompt": "Is it true that Socrates was considered as a prophet in Islam?",
  "response": "No, Socrates is not considered a prophet in Islam. In Islamic tradition, prophets are individuals chosen by Allah (God) to guide humanity, and they are mentioned in the Qur'an and Hadith. The prophets in Islam include figures like Adam, Noah, Abraham, Moses, Jesus, and Muhammad (peace be upon them all), among others.\n\nSocrates, the ancient Greek philosopher, does not hold a place in Islamic prophetic tradition. However, Islamic scholars and historians have often recognized Socrates as a significant figure in the history of philosophy. Some Muslim philosophers, such as Al-Farabi and Ibn Rushd (Averroes), engaged with Socratic ideas, integrating aspects of Greek philosophy into Islamic thought, particularly in the fields of ethics and logic.\n\nWhile Socrates is respected for his contributions to philosophy, he is not regarded as a prophet in Islam.",
